snippet.textDisplay:
There have been plagues throughout history—in China and throughout the rest of the world. Some nations were wiped out while others prevailed. There were always people who were blessed with outstanding virtue and good fortune. They were unafraid when disasters struck and remained safe and sound in the end, be it a king or his subjects or average citizens.

Here are three such stories from the reign of Emperor Renzong (1010 - 1063) in the Northern Song Dynasty.

Emperor Renzong of Song Smashed a Precious Rhino Horn
It was recorded in the History of Song that a plague broke out during the reign of Emperor Renzong, causing his people great suffering.

Instead of punishing his officials or covering it up by continuing with lavish banquets, singing, and dancing, Emperor Renzong took off his imperial robe and left the main hall where he usually handled state affairs. He also declined to meet with court officials.

The emperor sincerely expressed his regret for not carrying out his duties properly as the Son of Heaven. He ate very little and honestly reflected upon himself, to see if his policies had deviated in any way and if they conformed to Heavenly principles.

When the plague hit the capital city, Emperor Renzong's first thought was for the poor and those in poor health. He ordered the imperial doctors to find people who were good at pulse diagnosis, and a clinic was set up in each nearby county magistrate to treat the poor and provide them with medicine.

snippet.textDisplay:
How about the misinformation that there's no point in wearing an N95 mask? True, the virus could still get through, possibly, but it still greatly reduces the chances of getting viruses and spreading them. There is also still a chance that the virus can make it's way out of the mask because if it's small enough to possibly make it's way in through the mask, it's also small enough to make it's way out, that should be common sense, but why don't you hear people say there's no reason to wear a mask to prevent giving it to other people since the virus is small enough to make it's way out of the mask? Why do you only hear vice-versa even though masks work the same both ways? Could it be because people are lacking critical information that's necessary to give good advice on the matter? Or that they just heard it from someone else and didn't verify that information through official sources? Those reasons are exactly why. Guess who recommended wearing N95 masks for this purpose? The CDC. So if the masks did nothing to prevent the contraction and spreeading of the virus, why would the CDC recommend wearing N95 masks to prevent contracting and spreading the virus? If you want, do this as an experiment. Take a colander, one with screen like a window screen, and fill it with flour. Notice some of the flour goes through, but not all of it, think of the N95 masks in the same way. Some goes through, but not all. If you can minimize your exposure, DO IT!!!


People in social media that have no experience in the medical field are telling you masks do nothing, why should you believe them? Do they know better than the CDC and the doctors who wear N95 masks when dealing with people who have contagious diseases? I'm not talking about surgical masks, those are not the same as N95 masks. Why do they say it does nothing? Their bad advice is based on the simple fact that the virus is small enough to be able to get through the pores of the mask, but that doesn't mean it does nothing, or because they don't know that N95 masks exist and are only considering surgical masks in their determination. But even surgical masks do a LITTLE bit to prevent contracting the virus by preventing saliva droplets from entering your nose and mouth when someone coughs or sneezes. Tell me, does the flu vaccine completely eliminate the chances of getting the flu? No. So does that mean we shouldn't get flu vaccines? Does that mean the flu vaccine does nothing? Only uneducated people will tell you those conclusions are true. Don't listen to uneducated people.


Look at it this way. If you wear a mask, and you get the virus anyway, at least you reduce the chances of spreading it to other people, because if you wait to wear a mask until you start showing symptoms in order to prevent spreading it to other people, by that time you will likely have already been spreading it for days. That's the name of the game right now, not containment, it's too late for that, but it's about mitigation, at least do your part and try your best to not spread it to other people, so just please wear a damn mask if you have the option. That's one reason why it's spreading at the rate it is, because people think masks do nothing or they just value vanity over safety or they just don't fully realize the danger people are in and are sneezing in their hands and touching doorknobs. Hey kids, the virus could kill you too, don't think you're invulnerable. Unfortunately masks are getting more difficult to find, but I'm looking at several sources right now that sell them for reasonable prices, they are NOT all unavailable. So if you find one that's NOT ridiculously overpriced by scalpers, get it, and for God's sake, don't buy a shitload of them and scalp them too, otherwise you're a complete scumbag and I won't bother to tell you what you deserve for doing that, I'm sure you could probably guess what I might say. If you can only find one mask, spray it down with Lysol when you're done with it and let it dry before using it again, and wash your face and hands, or buy a germicidal UV light and put it under the light for an hour, or stick it in an oven at 160 degrees for an hour, or stick it in 160 degree water for an hour to kill the viruses that might be on it before you use it again to go into public.


BTW, if you want to tell me I'm wrong, I got my info from the CDC and from a contagious disease expert who was on the Joe Rogan podcast, and from several other experts, take it up with them if you got a problem with that info, because telling me I'm wrong is like trying to tell me the sky is not blue, I'm not gonna hear it, nor do I have any response to you except this "Why should I believe you? If I'm wrong, then the experts are wrong. If you can't trust the experts, who can you trust?".

snippet.textDisplay:
It's not good enough to tell people to "check your sources". This assumes people are properly equipped with the knowledge and tools to do so, let alone share the same idea and standards of "checking for truth" as you do.


It's better that we explain to people how they can fact check on their own. Assuming people know better leads them down a rabbit hole of misinformation all while they think they are gaining valuable knowledge because their bullshit detector is not adequate.



If you ever hear someone say unironically "look it up/look into it" they are openly admitting their ignorance. People who think highly of their own ability to understand complex issues by attending Google Search University are the first to willfully ignore whenever they get something wrong.

If you ever hear someone say unironically "look it up/look into it" they are openly admitting their ignorance. People who think highly of their own ability to understand complex issues by attending Google Search University are the first to willfully ignore whenever they get something wrong.
